⊕meta⊕
name = "explain-sky-workflow"
description = "Read one .sky file and emit a plain-English walkthrough so a user understands its triggers, node DAG, inputs, and edges without parsing the Unicode delimiters. Read-only."
trigger.manual = true
output_style = "terse"
max_budget_usd = 1
⊕⊕

※※
explain-sky-workflow — describe a .sky workflow in plain English (read-only)

WHAT
  Resolves one .sky file, then has Claude (haiku) read it and write a prose
  walkthrough: what triggers it, the node DAG in order, the --var inputs, what
  each node does, and the meaning of any when / chain_from / depends_on / loop
  edges. The file is NEVER modified.

DAG
  resolve ──> explain
  (bash)       (claude haiku, skills=[sky-workflow-authoring])

  resolve  verifies "$SKY_DIR/$SKY_NAME.sky" exists (exit 1 if not) and runs
           'sky describe' best-effort for extra context.
  explain  depends_on=[resolve], trigger_rule=all_success — only runs if the
           file actually resolved. Reads the file and writes prose. Read-only.

RUN
  sky run explain-sky-workflow --var dir=.sky/workflows --var name=my-workflow

VARS
  dir   directory containing the .sky file (no trailing slash).  -> $SKY_DIR
  name  workflow name WITHOUT the .sky extension.                -> $SKY_NAME
※※

※resolve※
Assert the target .sky exists ("$SKY_DIR/$SKY_NAME.sky"); exit 1
with a clear message if not. Then run `sky describe` best-effort for extra context the
explain step can use. Read-only: no rm, no mutation.
※※

§resolve§
bash_file = "./scripts/resolve.sh"
§§

※explain※
A cheap haiku node reads the resolved .sky and writes a plain-English
walkthrough (triggers, node DAG, --var inputs, per-node purpose, edge meanings). Runs
only if resolve succeeded (trigger_rule = all_success). Read-only — must not edit the
file. The sky-workflow-authoring skill teaches it the four-delimiter format.
※※

§explain§
model = "haiku"
depends_on = ["resolve"]
trigger_rule = "all_success"
skills = ["sky-workflow-authoring"]
§§

∆explain∆
Read the workflow file at {{dir}}/{{name}}.sky and write a plain-English walkthrough for a user who does NOT know the .sky Unicode-delimiter format. Do NOT modify the file — read only.

Context from the resolve step (path + optional `sky describe`):
$SKY_OUTPUT_RESOLVE

Cover, in this order, using clear headings and short paragraphs:

1. Summary — one sentence on what the workflow does.
2. Trigger — what makes it run (manual / github event / sky_event / cron) and any output_style or budget settings.
3. Inputs — every --var the user can pass, what each means, and how it maps to a $SKY_ variable.
4. Node DAG — list nodes in dependency order. For each: its id, type (bash / claude / http / script / loop / etc.), and one plain sentence on what it does.
5. Edges — explain the meaning of every depends_on, when condition, trigger_rule, chain_from, and loop.until / loop.max found. Translate gating semantics into plain language (e.g. "runs only if the previous step failed").
6. How to run — a copy-pasteable `sky run` command with the required --var flags.

Rules:
- Plain English. Do not show the raw Unicode delimiters; translate them.
- Be accurate to the actual file contents; do not invent nodes or vars.
- Keep it terse and machine-skimmable. No preamble, no closing pleasantries.
∆∆
